As a result, they ensure efficiency, reliability, and ease of integration with other systems by providing a standard approach to designing and building APIs. Here are the most used styles:  üîπSOAP: Mature, comprehensive, XML-based Best for enterprise applications  üîπRESTful: Popular, easy-to-implement, HTTP methods Ideal for web services  üîπGraphQL: Query language, request specific data Reduces network overhead, faster responses  üîπgRPC: Modern, high-performance, Protocol Buffers Suitable for microservices architectures  üîπWebSocket: Real-time, bidirectional, persistent connections Perfect for low-latency data exchange  üîπWebhook: Event-driven, HTTP callbacks, asynchronous Notifies systems when events occur  Over to you: Are there any other famous styles we missed?  ‚Äî Get a Free System Design PDF (158 pages) by subscribing to our weekly newsletter today: https://bit.ly/3FEGliw #systemdesign #coding #interviewtips .

post_text: There are different types of servers that play important roles in managing and distributing data across networks. üî• Here are some basic server types and what they do: üí° üåê Origin Server: This server holds the original copy of a website or web application. When you access a website, your browser sends a request to the origin server, which then sends back the necessary files to display the site on your screen.üåê Proxy Server: A proxy server acts as an intermediary between a client and another server. It can help improve network performance by caching frequently accessed files and web pages, as well as filtering requests for security purposes.üìß Mail Server: This type of server manages the sending and receiving of email messages. When you send an email, your email client communicates with the mail server to deliver the message to the recipient's mail server.üåê Web Server: A web server is a software program that delivers web content, such as HTML pages and images, to web browsers. It listens for incoming requests from clients and sends back the appropriate responses.üîç DNS Server: A DNS server translates human-readable domain names (like "google.com") into IP addresses that computers can understand. When you type a URL into your browser, your computer sends a request to a DNS server to find the corresponding IP address.‚úÖ Understanding these basic server types can help you better navigate and troubleshoot network issues. post_text: Use React? Render large lists efficiently with react-window: https://lnkd.in/etNN94TH ~ a small library for virtualizing lists & grids. Renders what users can see vs. all your items at once.If you've used React Virtualized for this before, it's by the same author Brian Vaughn, (but is far smaller) and a better fit if targeting mobile web given the smaller library size. A quick Movies demo using react-window can be found here: https://lnkd.in/edAK3HR8I've enjoyed using react-window on a few projects where list virtualization was a better fit for the UX. There are of course trade-offs with infinite scrolling patterns like this (e.g. with CLS, Load More) and I've written about them here: https://lnkd.in/eQc8mGQyIn case you're interested in learning more about list virtualization in React with plenty of examples, there's a great guide over on web(dot)dev too by Houssein Djirdeh and Jason Miller: https://lnkd.in/erqqabkV :)#softwareengineering #javascript #webdevelopment

name: Rinat (4rontender) Valiullov
title: Frontend Developer
post_text: Payment through scanning QR code is very common but do you know how many ways there are to do it? There are 4 ways, no matter whether you‚Äôre using PayPal, Stripe, Paytm, WeChat, or Alipay. Is this surprising to you? To understand this, we will answer to questions. The first question is who presents the QR code:1. You can present the QR code and the merchant scans the code for payment. This is called ‚Äòconsumer-presented mode, and what the merchant does is direct debit your account.2. Obviously, the other way is that the merchant presents the QR code for you to scan to pay the due amount. This is called ‚Äòmerchant-presented mode‚Äô and you grant the direct credit from your account.The second question is whether the QR code is dynamic or static:1. A dynamic QR code means the QR code will be generated when you present it, or it will automatically regenerate every few seconds. Because it is dynamically generated, it may contain rich information, such as the amount due, transaction type, etc.2. A static QR code is generated once and used everywhere. Usually, it only contains the account information. So there are 2*2=4 ways to scan a QR code, which are:1. Consumer-presented mode + static QR code2. Consumer-presented mode + dynamic QR code3. Merchant-presented mode + static QR code4. Merchant-presented mode + dynamic QR codeI‚Äôve created an image to illustrate these 4 cases and their classic scenarios. üëâ Over to you: I‚Äôve marked one of the scan-to-pay scenarios with a red alert symbol to indicate that a risk is present. Do you know why it is high risk?¬†‚ÄîJoin a growing community of more than 100,000 readers who love System Design. Subscribe here: https://bit.ly/3FEGliw¬†#systemdesign #coding #interviewtips.

post_text: Soon you'll be able to use the secret behind Angular and NestJS Frameworks in vanilla JavaScript ü§Øüî•JS Decorators are finally moving forward in the language, it's been 4 years since the first idea, and in April it was promoted to TC39's Stage 3 ü§ØI built a super video tutorial showing in practice a very useful application that monitors all incoming HTTP requests and responses and plots the data on a graph from a terminal üò¨This is a complex functionality that will open your mind to think of much more use cases than just Logging User's actions with Decorators (as I see often when teaching about it)I say decorators are the secret for NestJS and Angular frameworks because they use them for almost everything.They inject dependencies, they build routes, they handle state, they override regular classes to become DB Entities, and much more.I think the Node.js project will also benefit as we can reuse a lot of code and intercept the default behavior of functions, classes, and properties with slight changes.In this video, I also will show you a library that helps a lot to build interfaces on the terminal, the blessed-contrib library.Ah and the last thing, I've been publishing blooper reels after the video so you can enjoy my recording mistakes in all my recent videos.Although today, even my cat came to distract me and to be part of the class üòπI hope you enjoy it!üëâüèª https://lnkd.in/dKMguVKCComment here, what are your opinions about JS Decorators, I'd love to discuss it with you about it!#javascript #tc39 #decorators #newstoday #video #tutorial #100daysofcode

name: Svetlana P.
title: Senior Software Developer/ML Engineer ‚Äì Yandex
intro: Currently I'm working in the Yandex.Weather team, we are making the weather forecast using ML for millions of users. I'm an ML engineer and a backend developer at the same time. As an ML specialist I've worked with Catboost (Gradient Boosting on Decision Trees from Yandex) as well as with Neural Networks. This includes the following: processing of Big data using Yandex internal MapReduce tools, building a training set, training the model, making experiments with new features and new model settings, the quality control and assessment of metrics. As a backend developer, I'm responsible for the pipeline, that can automatically train a new model, compare it with the current one and put it into production. I'm using Python for ML experiments and C++ for backend. I've been a mentor for ML interns several times. I often participate in ML conferences as a listener as well as a speaker.Currently I'm working in the Yandex.Weather team, we are making the weather forecast using ML for millions of users. New loss function.Online advertising , Real time bidding.In general there are two task in real time bidding.First is a task of optimizing requests choice, second is a optimizing bid prices.A first task answers on a question , what need to buy, to get a revenue.The revenue is get from the target events: Clicks, Conversions ‚Ä¶So we may make a model that predict the events. It‚Äôs a classification task and may be solve as usual classification problem of binary classification.A second task answers on a question , what price need, to get a more benefit and win an auction .I consider the second task.The second is more complex, need increase number of win bids. Because only a wining bid gives revenue.The trivial solution is to set a bid price little smaller then an expected benefit, for example smaller by 10 % . But this solution is not optimal when there is a limit of our budget, and limits our benefit with 10%.Not bad solution is predict a probability of win and if the probability smaller then a given value increase a bid price. It‚Äôs a classification task too.But there is another way. Lets try to find an optimal price of the bid that layers between the loss price and win price, said for the same requests. And then if the win probability for this bid price smaller then some value, we increase the bid price.At first glance, this is a regression problem. But there is one problem. We only know the cost of losing when we lose the auction, but we don't know the next win price. In another case, we know the winning price when we won the auction, but we do not know the price of the next loss.And in general the bid price is a function of an input request. That is a set of categorical and numerical values.Such as : exchange id, app id, city, hour, day of week, language , and so on.Our model need to predict an optimal price for each request.My approach is to use a custom loss function that solves the problem. (I called loss YuLoss.)The loss function is based with MSE loss with little changes, or may base with any other regression loss.The main idea is :If the prediction price less or equivale then the loss price we penalty our model.If the prediction price more then the loss price we don‚Äôt penalty our model with MSE loss.If the prediction price less or equavile then the win price we don‚Äôt penalty our model.If the prediction price more then the win price we penalty our model with MSE loss.MSE (target, prediction) , if prediction <= target and result == no win else 0YuLoss =MSE (target, prediction), if prediction > target and result == win else 0The Model was made with using Catboost lib:Inputs: a list of vectors of categorical features.Targets : a list of prices and results - win/ no win.Data set of 10 M rows.The solution has given the optimal prices that in sum less then initial prices on 70 %.By the way a win rate decrease only 5%.The experiment was made with A\ B test.

post_text: https://lnkd.in/g5Ft2UW5Random ml engineer thoughts on the regulation of the generative field in a thread, in short - at which level fair use ends? For me, description models like classification/segmentation/embedding ones seem fine.But the CLIP model is also descriptive, you can't reproduce images easily from this. SD used a pre-trained and freezed CLIP model, and CLIP itself seems as fair use.But even if you use just CLIP and optimize in pixel space you may reproduce Getty watermark or some artist style (vqvae+clip or disco diffusion or even old deep dream algo). And SD itself generates some styles not only because it used them during the training, but also because CLIP pretraining knows them already. So if CLIP is also not fair use we should start suing OpenAI.But CLIP is a "descriptive" model, so should we change the "fair use" of other descriptive models (like classification/segmentation/etc.), and how we can prove that smth was used and that model in pipeline influence someones "style" (CLIP or SD)?So no we can either ban all the "fair use" or not change it at all.

post_text: Doing a postdoc will not enhance your career prospects outside of academia. Just the opposite. It will damage your prospects. If you‚Äôre in a postdoc now, please don‚Äôt rationalize staying longer by telling yourself you have time to decide what to do next, or that your postdoc is somehow adding valuable experience. Top companies don‚Äôt want PhDs to gain even more academic experience. They want you to gain on the job training. And they want you to start now. I hate seeing PhDs chase low paying postdocs for years only to have it used against them when they finally realize they won‚Äôt ever be a tenured professor - or worse, they become tenured and quickly as ‚ÄúThis is it? I have to do the work of 10 people for half of what I would make in industry?‚Äù If you want to stay in a postdoc - that, of course, is up to you. But stay in it with eyes wide open knowing you are decreasing your viability in industry with each day that passes. #phd #phds #postdoc #postdocs #phdlife #phdchat #phdjobs #phdcareers #phdstudents #phdstudent #academicchatter

post_text: Last few weeks were really sad for a lot of bright and smart people. We saw a lot of #layoffs posts and people asked me to refer them, help to find the next opportunity and the job.I helped people and connect with my other friends from other companies as well, helped with mock interviews and reviewed a lot of CVs. And I realized - people looking for a tool to find the job referrals and mock interviews faster and in an automation way to do it instead of tons of WhatsUp and Telegram channels, Google Spreadsheets and chats in LinkedIn. We built a service to help people to find the job referrals faster, find and help people with job interviews and I‚Äôm glad to share - https://referrs.me.I truly believe the idea of the community for such things, a lot of great and bright people looking the job now and a lot of bright people can refer them or know somebody who can refer. We are just lunching and as we saw - a lot of people in difficult financial situations now - so we made this service completely FREE. We are engineers who want to help other people to find the job faster, because we know how hard is it. If you have any questions or suggestions about the service - don‚Äôt hesitate to send me the feedback anywhere.Also - as our service is the community - I would like to ask you to share this service with your friends, colleagues, because maybe not their, but people whom they know - looking the referrals right now.#layoff #job #community #people #help #automation #jobinterviews #engineers #opportunity #share #referrals #referrals #mockinterviews #mockinterview
